<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>See, there's a difference between RPing up to standards and RPing within a setting framework.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Agreed.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>There's also a difference between role-playing wrong and role-playing in a manner that doesn't mesh with someone's style.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Also agreed.  Although while you and I see this, I have run into and witnessed many people here who do not see the difference.  For them, if your roleplaying doesn't mesh with their style, then you are roleplaying wrong.  And the will let you know that.  Loudly.  OOC.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> I could infer from this post that anybody you are not willing to role-play with is role-playing &quot;wrong&quot; in your mind.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Not at all.  From roleplaying so long in EQ, and some of the memories I have of random meetings that turned into interesting stories, I know I am missing out on some good roleplay by limiting myself to only those I know.<br>
<br>
I also know I am escaping a lot of OOC grief, once again from experience.<br>
<br>
Simply put, it has reached critical mass for me.  The ooc grief I avoid outweighs the good roleplay I miss.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If someone is not seperating themselves from their character are they role-playing at all? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
*grins*  I'd answer that, but then I'd be accused of telling people how to roleplay.<br>
<br>
But not saying that it is wrong, I was really surprised at how many roleplayers are just playing themselves in Norrath.<br>
<br>
<br>
